I had some trouble setting up a custom error page for my app. I found that the _500.tsx page only seems to show up when I run the app in preview mode. Is there a way I can make it appear in dev mode? In dev mode, the error message is quite descriptive, but I'm wondering if it's possible to show the custom _500.tsx page instead of the default dev error page.

I have a handler intentionally throwing an error:

```ts
export const handler: Handlers<Props> = {
  async GET(_req, ctx) {
    throw new Error('Some error inside the handler');
  }
};
```

When I run in dev mode using `deno run -A --watch=static/,routes/ dev.ts`, I see this screen:

![image](https://github.com/denoland/fresh/assets/57905553/2b1c562d-49ca-4d74-a2ac-0c2611951ba7)

When running in preview mode with `deno run -A main.ts`, this is the screen that appears (my _500.tsx component):

![image](https://github.com/denoland/fresh/assets/57905553/4414fcf3-c215-4d21-9807-49e951ceced3)

These are my dev.ts and main.ts files:

`dev.ts`
```ts
#!/usr/bin/env -S deno run -A --watch=static/,routes/

import dev from 'fresh/dev.ts';
import config from './fresh.config.ts';

import '$std/dotenv/load.ts';

await dev(import.meta.url, './main.ts', config);
```

`main.ts`
```ts
/// <reference no-default-lib='true' />
/// <reference lib='dom' />
/// <reference lib='dom.iterable' />
/// <reference lib='dom.asynciterable' />
/// <reference lib='deno.ns' />

import '$std/dotenv/load.ts';

import { start } from 'fresh/server.ts';
import manifest from './fresh.gen.ts';
import config from './fresh.config.ts';

await start(manifest, config);
```

Fresh version: 1.5.2
Deno version: 1.37.2

Thanks in advance :)

I was thinking of doing a PR for this, but realized it's probable best to check interest first. Similar to the reasoning for having `ctx.destination` in middleware, it would be nice for middleware/handlers/async routes to check if the current request is a partial. It's currently possible to do this by checking the URL `?fresh-partial=true`, but this feels a bit brittle (`PARTIAL_SEARCH_PARAM` is not exported).

My use case is having a form both be usable with the regular action, and when updating via partials. For instance, if a `<form>` posts to `/foo` and we want to return partials:

- One way would be to always render partials on the `/foo` endpoint, but this becomes weird if users disable their JS, where we get a strange result back (partial content)
- Another way is to create both a `/routes/foo` and `/routes/partials/foo` and set `action="/foo" f-partial="/partials/foo"` on the form. but it's annoying to have to duplicate the handling of the form in both places
- The way I intended to do it is to only have one the `/foo` route, but check if it's a partial (via query param currently). We first handle the form, then if it's a partial we return partial content, if not we redirect to a suitable place after the form

To make the last point easier it would be great if there was something built in to do something like the below:

```tsx
export const handler: Handlers<unknown, unknown> = {
  GET(req, ctx) {
    const fd = await req.formData();
    // Handle the form

    if (ctx.isPartial) return ctx.render();

    return new Response(undefined, {
      status: 303,
      headers: { location: '/' },
    });
  },
};
```

Another possible solution would be to export a helper function for checking this:
```tsx
import { isPartial } from '$fresh/server.ts';

    if (isPartial(req)) return ctx.render();
    // or
    if (isPartial(ctx)) return ctx.render();
```

